<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-706-117  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 706 117.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 17 1990 n331 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC reinstates ONA: wants to beef up enhanced-services safeguards.andO;(Open Network Architecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FCC has issued new rules regulating how the Bell companies mayprovide enhanced services in response to an appeals court's rulingwhich rejected previous FCC regulation.andP;  Bell companies must nowgive deployment schedules for services including Signaling System7, integrated, digital network, and advanced intelligent-networkservices.andP;  These schedules are designed to give users andenhanced-service providers a better idea as to the availability ofthe Bells' services.andP;  The new rules re-enforce the FCC'scommitment to Open Network Architecture (ONA), which forces theBells to offer other enhanced-service providers access to theirlocal networks on an equal level to that which the Bells givetheir own subsidiaries.andP;  New accounting guidelines are also partof the FCC's newer regulatory plan, called Computer Inquiry III,which replaced a structurally based set of rules implemented in1980 called Computer Inquiry II.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionTelephone CompaniesGovernment RegulationTelecommunications ServicesBell Regional Holding CompaniesInformation Services.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   BOCs andamp; enhanced services: a decade of change. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>